This is the "Sounds American" channel.

3
00:00:10,280 --> 00:00:14,600
In this video we're going to talk about
the American vowel sound /æ/,

4
00:00:15,940 --> 00:00:17,520
as in the word "cat."

5
00:00:19,600 --> 00:00:22,140
You can also hear this sound in words like

6
00:00:22,240 --> 00:00:23,040
"at,"

7
00:00:23,340 --> 00:00:23,980
"half,"

8
00:00:24,360 --> 00:00:25,160
"man,"

9
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:26,720
or "laugh."

10
00:00:28,160 --> 00:00:33,160
We'll be using a special phonetic symbol - /æ/ - for this sound.

11
00:00:35,200 --> 00:00:40,920
The /æ/ is specific to English, as the majority of languages don’t have this sound.

12
00:00:41,360 --> 00:00:46,960
That's the reason why many people distort the /æ/ or replace it with other vowels.

13
00:00:47,480 --> 00:00:51,440
Let's learn how to pronounce this sound the right (American) way.

14
00:00:52,440 --> 00:00:52,940
OK.

15
00:00:53,180 --> 00:00:58,620
To pronounce the /æ/ sound, you should focus on the correct position of your tongue and jaw.

16
00:00:59,700 --> 00:01:02,880
Open your mouth as wide as possible,

17
00:01:03,880 --> 00:01:06,800
slightly spread your lips, and tense them.

18
00:01:11,840 --> 00:01:15,520
Tense your tongue, flatten it, and push it forward.

19
00:01:16,480 --> 00:01:19,940
Your tongue should be positioned very low in your mouth.

20
00:01:21,400 --> 00:01:25,600
The tip of your tongue should be touching the back of your bottom front teeth.

21
00:01:28,060 --> 00:01:31,880
Remember, the /æ/ is a very open vowel sound,

22
00:01:32,180 --> 00:01:36,360
so your jaw should be very low and your tongue should be very flat.

23
00:01:37,560 --> 00:01:39,600
Now, let's try saying it:

24
00:01:39,960 --> 00:01:40,980
/æ/

25
